tual discipline. Reframing the way we think about some of the most consequential political events of the era, Gandhi presents moral imperfectionism as the lost tradition of global democratic thought and offers it to us as a key to democracy’s future. In doing so, she defends democracy as a shared art of living on the other side of perfection and mounts a postcolonial appeal for an ethics of becoming common.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnti-imperialist movementszIndia. 0aDemocracyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPostcolonialismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPostcolonialismzIndia. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ademocracy, ethics, postcolonialism, transnational, self fashioning, discipline, control, politics, political science, history, nonfiction, anticolonialism, empire, resistance, rebellion, military, mutiny, violence, gandhi, perfectionism, imperialism, fascism, authority, government, power, repression, race, racism, india, abnegation, morality, war, mundane, ordinary, common, community, philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022601987140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226020075423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226020075/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles